oss?\nActually, wait. Let me re-read the initial state. The crosses were at (16, 14), (16, 20), (16, 32), (16, 44). After moving (16, 14) to (16, 26), the crosses are at (16, 26), (16, 32), (16, 44). So the cross at (16, 20) was removed.\nBut (16, 20) is adjacent to (16, 14) (they're next to each other). Maybe when I selected (16, 14), the game also \"consumed\" the adjacent cross at (16, 20)?\nOr maybe the move from (16, 14) to (16, 26) \"jumped over\" (16, 20) and removed it, like in checkers?\nThis is interesting. Let me continue and see what happens when I move other crosses.\nNow I have crosses at (16, 26), (16, 32), (16, 44). Let me click (16, 26) to see where it can move.", "kind": "reasoning", "inContext": false}, {"label": "TOOL CALL: python", "content": "<tool_call>\n<function=python>\n<parameter=code>\n# Click the cross at (16, 26) to see its highlights\naction([{'action': 'MOUSE', 'row': 16, 'col': 26}])\n\nseg = current_frame.segmentation\nprint(\"After clicking cross at (16, 26):\")\nfor n in seg['nodes']:\n    if n['color'] in ('N', 'G', 'g'):\n        boundary = n['boundary']\n        center_row = sum(p[0] for p in boundary) // len(boundary)\n        center_col = sum(p[1] for p in boundary) // len(boundary)\n        if n['pixels'] > 5 or (n['color'] == 'g' and center_row > 5):\n            print(f\"  {n['color']}: center=({center_row}, {center_col}), pixels={n['pixels']}\")\n</parameter>\n</function>\n</tool_call>", "kind": "tool", "inContext": true}, {"label": "TOOL RESULT: python", "content": "After clicking cross at (16, 26):\n  G: center=(16, 26), pixels=20\n  N: center=(16, 26), pixels=12\n  N: center=(16, 32), pixels=12\n  g: center=(15, 38), pixels=2\n  N: center=(16, 44), pixels=12\n  g: center=(16, 37), pixels=2\n  g: center=(16, 40), pixels=2\n  g: center=(18, 38), pixels=2\n  N: center=(52, 44), pixels=12", "kind": "tool", "inContext": true}], "hasExactModelContext": false, "requestIndexWithinTurn": null, "messageCount": 0}, "context": {"s